column169: Prelim report: Bilateral median nerve somatosensory evoked potentials were abnormal. Absence of cortical and subcortical responses, with presence of brachial plexus response is suggestive of lesion or compression of the neural pathway at the level of, or above the  pheripheral nerve. Bilateral tibial nerve somatosensory evoked potentials were abnormal. Absence of cortical and subcortical responses, with presence of popliteal fossa response is suggestive of lesion or compression of the neural pathway at the level of, or above the  pheripheral nerve. Bilateral Brainstem auditory evoked potentials are absent. The wave I could not be recorded bilaterally, this is suggestive of a lesion at the level of inner ear. However midbrain pathology cannot be ruled out. Bilateral absence of cortical response from median nerve SSEPs are associated with poor prognosis.

column169: We just performed SSEPs (UE+LE) and BAEPs on this 75 yo M who suffered a cardiac arrest. I remotely supervised the testing and personally reviewed the informaction collected and available. Findings: MS: A cortical negative-positive-negative-positive complex was recorded with latencies for the N20 and P30 waveforms of 24.3 and 31.7 ms, respectively. Sub-cortical negative waves were recorded at 16.2 and 11.8 ms at the cervical and Erb's points, respectively. MD: A cortical negative-positive-negative- positive complex was recorded with latencies for the N20 and P30 waveforms of 24.5 and 31.2 ms, respectively. Sub-cortical negative waves were recorded at 16.2 and 11.5 ms at the cervical and Erb's points, respectively. TS: No cortical responses could be clearly identified. Sub-cortical negative waves were recorded at 30.0 and 7.0 ms at the cervical and popliteal points, respectively. TD: A cortical positive-negative-positive complex was recorded with latencies for the P40 and P60 waveforms of 46.0 and 65.0 ms, respectively. Sub-cortical negative waves were recorded at 31.7 and 7.7 ms at the cervical and popliteal points, respectively. AS: Left ear recordings: Waves I, III and V were identified at peak latencies of 2.0, 3.8 and 6.5 ms, respectively. AD: Left ear recordings: Waves I, III and V were identified at peak latencies of 1.6, 3.9 and 6.2 ms, respectively. IMPRESSIONS: UE: Somatosensory Evoked Potentials with morphology, latencies (including the ones from the N20 waveforms), amplitude and L/R differences within NORMAL limits for the age range. LE: Somatosensory Evoked Potential ABNORMAL for absence of cortical responses with sub-cortical cervical and peripherals preserved, suggestive of a lesion or compression of the neural pathway at the level of, or above the dorsal column nucleus, most likely at the cortical level on the RIGHT hemisphere. The SEP elicited when the right Tibial nerve was stimulated is within NORMAL limits for the age range. BAEPs: Brainstem Auditory Evoked Potentials with morphology, peak latencies, inter-peak intervals, L/R differences and ratios within NORMAL limits for the age range. OPINION: These results point to a focal Parietal cortex lesion of the RIGHT hemisphere, with preservation of the brainstem function.

column169: Bedside somatosensory evoked potentials in response to bilateral median and tibial nerve stimulation were recorded.  Additionally, brainstem potentials in response to bilateral auditory stimulation were recorded.  Stimulation of the median nerves resulted in peripheral, brainstem and cortical responses recorded bilaterally from both hemispheres.  Cortical responses, while present, were grossly delayed.  Stimulation of the tibial nerves bilaterally did not result in cortical responses.  Auditory stimulation resulted in normal brainstem waves to be recorded bilaterally that, given the patients age, were within normal latency limits.  Taken together and given the patients age, presence of cortical median nerve SSEP's and normal brainstem potentials are indicative of functioning brainstem and somatosensory thalamocortical radiations.

column169: We just performed SSEPs (UE+LE) and BAEPS on this 55 yo M with severe Diabetes with vascular complica- tions, peripheral neuropatthy, CAD, Renal failure in treatmen with dyalisis, and apparently presented to the ER b/c of a MI and cardiac arrest. I remotely supervised the testing but personally checked the collected and available information and this is my interpretation: SSEPs: MS: A cortical negative-positive-negative-positive complex was recorded with latency for the N20 waveform of 26.0 ms. Sub-cortical negative waves were recorded at 14.2 and 10.2 ms at the cervical and Erb's points, respectively. MD: A cortical negative-positive-negative-positive complex was recorded with latency for the N 20 waveform of 26.3 ms. Sub-cortical negative waves were recorded at 13.8 and 9.8 ms at the cervical and Erb's points, respectively.  INTERPRETATION: 0isy Somatosensory Evoked Potentials of Median nerves with appropriate morphology, but AB0RMAL for prolonged latencies at all levels, suggestive of a lesion or compression of the neural pathway at the level of the peripheral nerves.  TS: 0 cortical/subcortical responses could be identified. TD: 0 cortical/subcortical responses could be identified. BAEPs: AS: Left ear recordings: Waves I, III and V were identified at peak latencies of 2.3, 5.2 and 7.2 ms, respec- tively. AD: Right ear recordings: Waves I, III and V were identified at peak latencies of 1.9, 4.1 and 5.8 ms, respectively.  INTERPRETATION: Brainstem Auditory Evoked Potentials with acceptable morphology, but AB0RMAL for delayed peak latencies of all waves on the Left side, as well as, prolonged inter-peak intervals I-III and I-V also on the Left side, suggestive of a lesion or compression on the auditory pathway at the level of the  upper Medulla/lower Pons on the LEFT side. The BAEP elicited when the Right ear was stimulated is within 0RMAL limits.  OPINION: These studies are suggestive of a bilateral, patchy compromise of the cortex, with major com- promise at the convexity than paramedial, with partially preserved electrographic brainstem activty as it can be seen on ischemic/hypoxic encephalopathies. The bilatereal presence of the N20 waveforms at least theoretically will give this patient a a good survival and neurological outcome prog0ses.

column169: We just performed SSEPs (UE+LE) on this 82 yo M, who apparently suffered a cardiac  arrest. I remotely supervised the testing, but personally reviewed the information collected and available and this is my impression: SSEPs: MS: No cortical responses could be identified. Sub-cortical negative waves were re- corded at 14.0 and 10.3 ms, at the cervical and Erb's points, respectively. MD: No cortical responses could be identified. Sub-cortical negative waves were re- corded at 13.3 and 9.7 ms, at the cervical and Erb's points, respectively. INTERPRETATION: Somatosensory Evoked Potentials of Median Nerves ABNORMAL for absence of cortical responses, with sub-cortical cervical and peripherals preserved, suggestive of a lesion or compression of the neural pathways at the level of, or above the dorsal columns nuclei, most likely at the cortical level, bilaterally.  TS: No cortical responses could be identified. Sub-cortical negative waves were re- corded at 27.0 and 8.3 ms, at the cervical and popliteal points, respectively. TD: No cortical responses could be identified. Sub-cortical negative waves were re- corded at 28.3 and 9.7 ms, at the cervical and popliteal points, respectively. INTERPRETATION: Somatosensory Evoked Potentials of Tibial Nerves ABNORMAL for absence of cortical responses, with sub-cortical cervical and peripherals preserved, suggestive of a lesion or compression of the neural pathways at the level of, or above the dorsal columns nuclei, most likely at the cortical level, bilaterally. BAEPs: AS: Left ear recordings: No signals could be identified. AD: Right ear recordings: Waves I. III and V were identified at peak latencies of 2.4,  4.8 and 7.0 ms, respectively. INTERPRETATION: Brainstem Auditory Evoked Potentials of the RIGHT ear with acceptable morphology, but ABNORMAL for delayed peak latency of wave V, as well as, prolonged in- ter-peak intervals III-V and I-V, suggestive of a lesion or compression of the auditory pathway at the level of the upper Pons/lower Midbrain on the RIGHT side. No BAEP could be elicited from the LEFT ear.  IMPRESSION: These studies suggest extensive, bilateral lesion of the Parietal cortex at the convexity and parasagital, of both hemispheres. The electrophysiological brainstem function is also impaired on both sides. These lesions can be compatibles with the ones  seen in an extensive hypoxic/ischemic encephalopathy

column169: We just practiced SSEPs(UE+LE)and BAEPs on this 65 yo diabetic M who recently have a CVA,  and suffered a cardiac arrest. I remotely supervised the testing, but, personally reviewed all the information collected and available and this is my impression.  SSEPs: MS: No cortical responses could be identified. Sub-cortical negative waves were recorded at 20.3 and 14.0 ms at the cervical and Erb's points, respectively. MD: No cortical responses could be identified. Sub-cortical negative waves were recorded at 19.7 and 13.3 ms at the cervical and Erb's points, respectively. INTERPRETATION: Somatosensory Evoked Potentials of Median nerves very ABNORMAL for absen- ce of cortical responses with sub-cortical cervical and peripherals preserved but delayed,  suggestive of lesions or compressions of the neural pathways at the level of, or above the dorsal columns nuclei, most likely at the cortical level on both hemispheres, as well  as, at the level of the peripheral nerve, also on both sides.  LE: No responses could be registered from the Tibial nerves. There existed important amount of oedema at the distal segments of both lower extremities.  BAEPs; AS: Left ear recordings: Waves I, III and V were identified at peak latencies of 2.1,  5.6 and 7.3 ms, respectively.   AD: Right ear recordings: Waves I, III and V were identified at peak latencies of 2.4,  4.9 and 7.4 ms, respectively. INTERPRETATION: Brainstem Auditory Evoked Potentials with acceptable morphology, but  ABNORMAL for delayed peak latencies of all waves, on both sides, as well as, prolonged inter-peak intervals I-III, III-V and I-V, also on boh sides, suggestive of a lesion or compression of the auditory pathways at the level of the peripheral nerve, on both sides.  IMPRESSION: These studies suggest complete, extended lesions of the Parietal cortex of  the convexities from both hemispheres, in a severely diabetic patient with affection of the peripheral nerves of 4 limbs and cranial nerves. The cortical lesions are compatible with sequelae of a hypoxic/ischemic encephalopaty with preserved electrophysiological  brainstem function. The bilateral absence of the N20 cortical responses on the Median nerve SSEPs of this patient, give him a very bad neurological outcome and survival  prognoses.

I remotely supervised the tesging but personally reivewed the information collected and available and this is my impression:  SSEPs:  MS: A cortical negative-positive-negative-positive complex was recorded with latencies for the N20 and P30 waveforms of 26.7 and 33.2 ms, respectively. Sub-cortical negative waves were recorded at 14.7 and 9.3 ms at the cervical and Erb's points, respectively. MD: A cortical negative-positive-negative-positive complex was recorded with latencies for the  N20 and P30 waveforms of 22.3 and 28.3 ms, respectively. Sub-cortical negative waves were recorded at 14.8 and 9.3  ms at the cervical and Erb's points, respectively.  INTERPRETATION: Somatosensory Evoked Potential of the Left Median nerve slightly ABNORMAL for delayed latency of  the cortical responses, with the sub-cortical and peripherals preserved and normal, suggestive of a lesion or compression  of the neural pathway at the level of, or above the dorsal columns nuclei, most likely at the cortical level of the RIGHT  hemisphere. The SEP elicited when the Right Median nerve was stimulated is within NORMAL limits for the age range.  TS: A cortical positive-negative-positive complex was recorded with latencies for the P40 and P60 waveforms of 39.3 and  61.2 ms, respectively. Sub-cortical negative waves were recorded at 24.7 and 7.3 ms at the cervical and popliteal points, respectively. TD: A cortical positive-negative-positive complex was recorded with latencies for the P40 and P60 waveforms  of 41.3 and 60.5 ms, respectively. Sub-cortical negative waves were recorded at 24.7 and 8.3 ms at the cervical and popli- teal points, respectively.    INTERPRETATION: Somatosensory Evoked Potential of the Tibial nerves with morphology, latenciese, amplitude and L/R differences within NORMAL limits for the age range.  BAEPs: AS: Left ear recordings: Waves I, III and V were identifed at peak latencies of 2.3, 5.2 and 7.3 ms, respectively. AD: Right ear recordings: Waves I, III and V were identifed at peak latencies of 2.3, 5.3 and 6.8 ms, respectively. INTERPRETATION: Brainstem Auditory Evoked Potentials with appropriate morpology but ABNORMAL for delayed peak latencies of waves III and V bilaterally, as well as, prolonged inter-peak intervals I-III, and I-V, also bilate- rally, suggestive of a lesion or compression of the auditory pathway at the level of the upper Medulla/lower Pons, bilateral, but worse on the LEFT side.  IMPRESSSION: These studies point to a mild, localized lesion/compression of the Parietal cortex of the the convexity of the Right hemisphere, with compromise of the electrophysiological brainstem function. These lesions could be the result of a hypoxic/ischemic encephalopathy. The presence of one adequate and another inadequate N20 cortical responses of the Median nerve SEPs make the neurologic and survival prognoses of these patient uncertain.

column169: We just performed SSEPs (UE+LE) and BAEPs on this 53 yo F who apparently suffered a cardiac arrest. MD: A cortical negative-positive-negative-positive complex was recorded with latencies for the N20 and P30 waveforms of 30.7 and 41.0 ms, respectively. Sub-cortical negative waves were recorded at 13.5 and 8.8 ms, respectively.  INTERPRETATION: Somatosensory Evoked Potentials of Median nerves ABNORMAL for complete absence  of the RIGHT hemisphere, and delayed latencies in the LEFT, of the cortical responses, with sub-cortical cervical and peripherals preserved on both sides, suggestive of a lesion or compression of the neural pathway at the level  of, or above the dorsal columns nuclei on the RIGHT, and most-likely at the cortical level on the LEFT.  TS: No cortical responses could be identified. Sub-cortical negative waves were recorded at 32.0 and 7.7 ms at the  cervical and popliteal points, respectively.  TD: No cortical responses could be identified. Sub-cortical negative waves  were recorded at 27.7 and 7.0 ms at the cervical and popliteal points, respectively.  INTERPRETATION: Somatosensory Evoked Potentials of Tibial nerves ABNORMAL for complete, absence of  cortical responses, suggestive of a lesion or compression of the neural pathway at the level of, or above the dorsal  columns nuclei on both sides.  BAEPs:  AS: Left ear recordings: Waves I, III and V were identified at peak latencies of 2.0, 4.4 and 7.5 ms, respectively. AD: Right ear recordings: Waves I, III and V were identified at peak latencies of 2.3, 4.4 and 6.7 ms, respectively.  INTERPRETATION: Brainstem Auditory Evoked Potentials with acceptable morphology, but ABNORMAL for delayed peak latencies of wave V on both sides, as well as, prolonged inter-peak intervaks III-V and I-V, also on both sides, suggestive of a lesion or compression of the auditory pathway at the level of the upper Pons/lower Midbrain, on both sides but worse on the LEFT.  IMPRESSION: The findings of these tests point to an extense, complete lesion of the Parietal cortical areas on both  hemispheres with partial preservation of the convexity of the LEFT hemisphere, with compromised electrophysiological brainstem function. These problems could be compatible with lesions from an ischemic/anoxic encephalopathy. These finding in presence of only one and abnormal N20 waveform from the Median nerve SSEPs give this patient a bad neu- rological outcome prognosis, and, an uncertain survival one.

column169: 1. Upper Extremity SSEPs  from bilateral Median Nerve stimulation:  Technique:   Stimulation of left ulnar (US) and right ulnar (UD) nerves was performed simultaneously with stimulating electrodes positioned at the wrist, 1 cm apart (US, UD), with the positive electrode proximal to the negative electrode.  A uniform stimulus rate of  2.35Hz was used.  Two hundred and fifty six responses were averaged for each epoch.  Two epochs were obtained for each stimulus condition, including controls (no stimulus applied).  The observation interval was 100 ms.  Recording electrodes were positioned as follows:  Ch 1) right parietal cortex to frontal midline (P4/Fz); Ch 2) left parietal cortex to frontal midline (P3/Fz); Ch 2) mastoid to frontal midline (M/Fz); and Ch 4) left erb's point to right erb's point (EpS/EpD). Amplifier bandpass was 10 to 1000 Hz for Ch 1 and Ch 2; 100 to 1000 Hz for Ch 3 and Ch 4.  The patient reclined in the supine position, in a dimly lit room, with eyes gently closed.  Results:          Left Ulnar Nerve Stimulation (US): An evoked potential was recorded at Erb's point at 11.7 ms. Evoked responses were not recorded at the cervical spine, subcortically, or at the right parietal cortex. Interpretation:         The somatosensory evoked potentials from the left ulnar nerve are absent above the level of the left brachial plexus, suggestive of a diffuse brain injury.   Right Ulnar Nerve Stimulation (UD): An evoked potential was recorded at Erb's point at 11.2 ms. Evoked responses were not recorded at the cervical spine, subcortically, or at the left parietal cortex. Interpretation:         The somatosensory evoked potentials from the right ulnar nerve are absent above the level of the right brachial plexus, suggestive of a diffuse brain injury.    2. Lower Extremity SSEPs  from bilateral Posterior Tibial Nerve stimulation:  Technique:   Stimulation of left (TS) and right (TD) tibial nerves was performed simultaneously, with stimulation electrodes positioned at the medial malleolous, with the positive electrode proximal.  A uniform stimulus rate of  2.35Hz was used. Two hundred and fifty six responses were averaged for each epoch.  Two epochs were obtained for each stimulus condition, including controls (no stimulus applied).  The observation interval was 100 ms. Recording electrodes were positioned as follows:  Ch 1) midline parietal cortex to frontal midline (Pz/Fz); Ch 2) mastoid  to frontal midline (M/Fz); Ch 3) popliteal fossa (PF+/PF-). Amplifier bandpass was 10 to 1000 Hz for Ch 1, and 100 to 1000 Hz for Ch 2 and Ch 3.  The patient reclined in a supine position, in a dimly lit room, with eyes gently closed.  Results:          Left Posterior Tibial Nerve Stimulation (TS): Evoked responses were not recorded at the cervical spine, subcortically, or at the right parietal cortex. Interpretation:         The somatosensory evoked potentials from the left posterior tibial nerve are absent above the level of the left lumbar plexus, suggestive of a diffuse brain injury.   Right Posterior Tibial Nerve Stimulation (TD): Evoked responses were not recorded at the cervical spine, subcortically, or at the left parietal cortex. Interpretation:         The somatosensory evoked potentials from the right posterior tibial nerve are absent above the level of the right lumbar plexus, suggestive of a diffuse brain injury.    3. Impression:         The recording of brachial plexus SSEPs from US and UD and the visible evoked motor twitching in intrinsic hand muscles, bilaterally, confirmed adequate peripheral nerve stimulation was achieved. The absence of SSEPs at the level of the brainstem and cerebral cortex, bilaterally, suggests an extensive and diffuse brain injury.

column169: 55 yo male pt, who apparently suffered a cardiac or cardio-respiratory arrest, in which, it was when found. I remotely supervised the testing but personally reviewed all the in- formation recorded and available and this is my impression:  SSEs: MS: A cortical negative-positive-negative-positive complex was recorded with latencies  for the N20 and P30 waveforms of 19.2 and 29.3 ms, respectively. Sub-cortical negative waves were recorded at 15.3 and 10.2 ms at the cervical and Erb's points, respectively. MD: No cortical responses could be identified. Sub-cortical negative waves were recor- ded at 13.7 and 11.0 ms at the cervical and Erb's points, respectively. INTERPRETATION: Somatosensory Evoked Potential elicited from the Right Median nerve ABNORMAL for total abscense of cortical responses, suggestive of a lesion or compression of the neural pathway at the level of, or above the dorsal column nucleus, most likely at the  cortical level of the LEFT hemisphere. The SEP elicited from the Left Median nerve is within NORMAL limits for the age range.  TS: No cortical responses could be identified. Sub-cortical negative waves were recorded at 31.8 and 7.7 ms at the cervical and popliteal points, respectively. TD: No cortical responses could be identified. Sub-cortical negative waves were recorded at 30.3 and 8.8 ms at the cervical and popliteal points, respectively. INTERPRETATION: Somatosensory Evoked Potentials from the Tibial nerves ABNORMAL  for complete abscense of cortical responses, suggestive of a lesion or compression of the neural pathway, at the level of, or above the dorsal columns nuclei, most likely at the cortical level of BOTH hemispheres.  BAEPs: AS: Left ear recordings: Waves I, III and V were identified at peak latencies of 1.7, 5.4 and 6.8  ms, respectively. AD: Right ear recordings: Waves I, III and V were identified at peak latencies of 1.3, 3.6 and 5.7  ms, respectively. INTERPRETATION: Brainstem Auditory Evoked Potential elicited from the Left ear with appro- priate morphology, but ABNORMAL for delayed peak latencies of all waves beyond wave I on  the Left side, and prolonged inter-peak intervals I-III and I-V also in the Left side, suggestive of a lesion or compression of the auditory pathway at the level of the Upper Medulla/Lower Pons on the LEFT side. The BAEP elicited from the Right ear is within NORMAL limits for the age range.  IMPRESSION: The studies point to extended, multiple lesions of the Parietal cortex from both hemispheres, mainly at the para-median areas, but also at the convexity on the Right side, as  well as, to a unilateral compromise of the electrophysiological brainstem function. The findings  are compatible with those produced by an ischemic/hypoxic encephalopathy. Although, one of  the N20 cortical responses from the Median nerve SEPs is present, 3 out of the 4 cortical SEP  responses are not. Based on these findings and considerations, I believe this patient has very  somber prognoses for his neurological outcome and survival.

column169: We just performed SSEPs (UE) and BAEPs on this 56 yo F who apparently suffered a cardiac arrest. The lower extremity SSEPs were attempted. However, given the edema present at the exam time on the patient's feet and ankles, we did not obtain reliable data from these limbs. I remotely supervised the testing, but, personally reviewed the information recor- ded and available and this is my impression:  SSEPs:   MS: A cortical negative-positive-negative-positive complex was recorded with latencies  for the N20 and P30 waveforms of 28.3 and 36.7 ms, respectively. Sub-cortical negative waves were recorded at 17.3 and 13.5 ms at the cervical and Erb's points, respectively. MD: A cortical negative-positive-negative-positive complex was recorded with latencies  for the N20 and P30 waveforms of 30.0 and 38.7 ms, respectively. Sub-cortical negative waves were recorded at 17.0 and 12.0 ms at the cervical and Erb's points, respectively. INTERPRETATION: Somatosensory Evoked Potentials of Median nerves ABNORMAL for delayed latencies of the cortical and sub-cortical responses, suggestive of a lesion or compres- sion of the neural pathways at the level of the peripheral nerves.  BAEPs: AS: Left ear responses: Waves I, III and V were identified at peak latencies of 2.7,  4.8 and 6.4 ms, respectively. AD: Right ear responses: Waves I, III and V were identified at peak latencies of 2.5,  4.7 and 6.6 ms, respectively. INTERPRETATION: Brainstem Auditory Evoked Potentials with morphology, peak latencies, inter-peak intervals, L/R differences and ratios within NORMAL limits for the age range.

TS: No cortical responses could be identified. Sub-cortical negative waves were recorded at 27.3 and  6.3 ms at the cervical and popliteal points, respectively. column169: This afternoon we performed SSEPs (UE+LE) and BAEPs on this 53 yo F who apparently suffered a cardiac arrest and received CPR for approximately 40 minutes before coming to Hospital. I remotely supervised the testing, but personally reviewed the information recorded and available and this is my impression:  SSEPs:  MS: No cortical responses could be identified. Sub-cortical negative waves were recorded at 12.5 and 9.8 ms, at the  cervical and Erb's points, respectively. MD: No cortical responses could be identified. Sub-cortical negative waves were recorded at 12.8 and 10.3 ms, at the  cervical and Erb's points, respectively. INTERPRETATION: Somatosensory evoked potentials from Median nerves ABNORMAL for absence of cortical res- ponses with sub-cortical cervical and peripherals preserved, suggestive of a lesion or compression at the level of, or above the dorsal columns nuclei, most likely at the cortical level, on both hemispheres.  TS: No cortical responses could be identified. Sub-cortical negative waves were recorded at 30.7 and 10.7 ms, at the  cervical and Popliteal points, respectively. TD: No cortical responses could be identified. Sub-cortical negative waves were recorded at 29.5 and 11.5 ms, at the  cervical and Popliteal points, respectively. INTERPRETATION: Somatosensory evoked potentials from Tibial nerves ABNORMAL for absence of cortical res- ponses with sub-cortical cervical and peripherals preserved, suggestive of a lesion or compression at the level of, or above the dorsal columns nuclei, most likely at the cortical level, on both hemispheres.  BAEPs:  AS: Left ear recordings: Waves I, III and V were identified at peak latencies of 2.4, 4.9 and 8.4 ms, respectively. AD: Right ear recordings: Waves I, III and V were identified at peak latencies of 2.4, 4.8 and 8.0 ms, respectively. INTERPRETATION: Brainstem Auditory Evoked Potentials with acceptable morphology but ABNORMAL for de- layed peak latencies of all waves beyond wave I on both sides, as well as, prolonged inter-peak intervals I-III, and  I-V, also on both sides, suggestive of a lesion or compression of the auditory pathway at the level of the upper Me- dulla/lower Pons on both sides, but worse on the Left.  IMPRESSION: The findings of these studies point to a complete, bilateral lesion of the Parietal cortex from both hemispheres, with compromised electrographic brainstem function. These findings could be the ones found after  a hypoxic-ischemic encephalopathy. The bilateral absence of the N20 waveform at the cortical responses of the Median nerve SSEPs give this patient a very somber neurologic outcome and survival prognoses.

column169: We just performed SSEPs (UE+LE) and BAEPs on this 54 yo M who apparently had a cardiac arrest and was  found unconcious in cardio-respiratory arrest. I personally supervised the testing and reviewed the informa tion recorded and available and this is my impression:  Pt was not hypothermic but at the moment under hemo-dyalisis, Propofol at 50 mcg/hr, EEG shows burst- supression pattern. The pateint is a known diabetic with neuropathy. After several attemps, we were not able to collect anything different than electryc noise from the SSEPs.  BAEPs:  AS: Left ear recordings: Waves I, III and V were identified at peak latencies of 2.3, 5.2 and 8.3 ms, respectively. AD: Right ear recordings: Waves I, III and V were identified at peak latencies of 1.6, 4.4 and 7.2 ms, respectively. INTERPRETATION: Brainstem Auditory Evoked Potentials with poor but acceptable morpholgy, ABNORMAL for de- layed peak latencies of waves III and V on the left side, while only wave V at the right, and with prolonged inter- peak intervals I-III, III-V, and I-V on the left side while III-V and I-V on the right side suggestive of a lesion or  compression of the auditory pathways at the level of the upper Medulla/lower Pons on the LEFT side while at the upper Pons/lower Midbrain on the RIGHT one.    IMPRESSION: This data point to a bilateral compromise of the brainstem electrophysiological function. Although, it was impossible to collect any useful data from the SSEPs and therefore we can not try to infere a prognosis from  that data, I think this patient's neurological outcome's prognosis can not be good with a bilateral lesion of his brainstem.  P.S: If there is the opportunity the SSEPs must be attempted again at another time.

1. Upper Extremity SSEPs  from bilateral Median Nerve stimulation:  Results:          Left Median Nerve Stimulation (MS): An evoked potential was recorded at Erb's point at 10.7 ms and at the cervical spine at a peak latency of 16.7 ms. A veryu small NP response complex was recorded at the right parietal cortex with peak latencies of 25.3 ms and 34.0 ms (N20/P30), respectively.  Interpretation:         The somatosensory evoked potentials from the left median nerve are present and delayed at the level of the inferior brainstem, above which, nominal responses were recorded, suggesting a lesion or compression at the level of the brainstem on the left side.    Right Median Nerve Stimulation (MD): An evoked potential was recorded at Erb's point at 10.3 ms and at the cervical spine at a peak latency of 16.3 ms. An NP response complex was recorded at the left parietal cortex with peak latencies of 24.7 ms and 32.7 ms (N20/P30), respectively. Interpretation:         The somatosensory evoked potentials from the right median nerve are moderately abnormal at the level of the right brainstem.    2. Lower Extremity SSEPs  from bilateral Posterior Tibial Nerve stimulation:  Results:          Left Posterior Tibial Nerve Stimulation (TS): An evoked potential was recorded at the popliteal fossa at 14.0 ms. The evoked potential at the cervical spine was recorded at a peak latency of 37.3 ms. A nominal positive peak (P40) was recorded over midline parietal cortex at a peak latency of 54.5 ms. Interpretation:         The somatosensory evoked potentials from the left posterior tibial nerve are of poor morphology and are abnormally delayed with only nominal cortical responses recorded, suggestive of a lesion and/or compression at the level of the brainstem, or above, on the right side.  Right Posterior Tibial Nerve Stimulation (TD): An evoked potential was recorded at the popliteal fossa at 16.7 ms and at the cervical spine at a peak latency of 28.3 ms. An negative peak (N37) was recorded at the left parietal cortex with peak latency of 50.3 ms.  Interpretation:         The somatosensory evoked potentials from the right posterior tibial nerve are of poor morphology and are abnormally delayed with only nominal cortical responses recorded, suggestive of a lesion and/or compression at the level of the brainstem, or above, on the left side.  3. Brainstem Auditory Evoked Responses (BSER)  from bilateral auditory, click stimulation:   Left Auditory Stimulation (AS): Waves I, II, III and a Wave IV/V response complex were recorded at peak latencies of 1.9, 2.8, 4.7 and 6.8 ms, respectively. Interpretation:         The brainstem responses from left auditory stimulation are of good morphology but are abnormally delayed at the level of the superior brainstem on the right side. Right Auditory Stimulation (AD): Waves I, II, III and a Wave IV/V response complex were recorded at peak latencies of 2.1, 3.2, 4.5 and 7.0 ms, respectively. Interpretation:         The brainstem responses from right auditory stimulation are of good morphology but are abnormally delayed at the level of the superior brainstem on the left side.    4. Impression:         SSEPs from MS, MD, TS, TD and BSERs from AS and AD are abnormal. These data support bilateral, multi-focal injuries and/or compressions at levels from the superior brainstem to the cerebral cortices.

Sub-cortical negative waves were recorded at 15.8 and 10.8 ms at the cervical and Erb's points,  respectively.                                                                                                                        MD: A cortical negative-positive-negative-positive complex was recorded with latencies for the N20 and P30 waveforms of 25.3  and 35.7 ms, respectively. Sub-cortical negative waves were recorded at 17.3 and 11.2 ms at the cervical and Erb's points,  respectively.                                                                                     INTERPRETATION: Somatosensory Evoked Potential from the Right Median nerve ABNORMAL for delayed cortical responses  with sub-cortical cervical and peripherals preserved suggestive of a lesion or compression of the neural pathway at the level of,  or above the dorsal column nucleus on the LEFT hemisphere. The SEP elicited when the Left Median nerve was stimulated is  within NORMAL limits for the age range.  TS: No cortical responses could be identified. Sub-cortical negative waves were recorded at 27.3 and 6.7 ms at the cervical and  popliteal points, respectively.                                                                                                                        TD: A cortical positive-negative-positive complex was recorded with latencies for the P40 and P60 waveforms of 46.2 and 58.2  ms, respectively. Sub-cortical negative waves were recorded at 27.5 and 7.2 ms at the cervical and popliteal points, respectively. INTERPRETATION: Somatosensory Evoked Potential from the Left Tibial nerve ABNORMAL for absence of cortical responses  with sub-cortical cervical and peripherals preserved suggestive of a lesion or compression of the neural pathway at the level of,  or above the dorsal column nucleus on the RIGHT hemisphere. The SEP elicited when the Right Tibial nerve was stimulated is  within NORMAL limits for the age range.  BAEPs:  AS: Left ear recordings: Waves I, III and V were identified at peak latencies of 1.9, 4.0 and 6.1 ms, respectively.                                                                AD: Right ear recordings: Waves I, III and V were identified at peak latencies of 2.0, 4.2 and 6.1 ms, respectively.                                                              INTERPRETATION: Brainstem Auditory Evoked Potentials with morphology, peak latencies, inter-peak intervals, L/R differences  and ratios within NORMAL limits for the age range.                                                                                        IMPRESSION: The results of these studies point to a partial damage of the Parietal cortex on the Left hemisphere at the  convexity areas and of cortical and/or sub-cortical areas above of the brainstem of the Right one, with preserved electrographic  brain-stem function. These patchy cortico/subcortical lessions could be the result of a hypoxic-ischemic or other encephalopathies. The bilateral presence of the N20 waveforms from the cortical responses of this patient's Median nerve SSEPs make its  neurological outcome and survival prognoses good.

column169: This is a markedly abnormal study.   The left median nerve SSEP was abnormal. No clear subcortical response was obtained.    This suggests there is a lesion in the right hemisphere affecting ulnar and tibial nerve SSEPs.    Bilateral brainstem auditory evoked potentials were abnormal. The latency of wave I was delayed indicating peripheral hearing disorder. The waves III, and V were recorded but delayed.

column169: 1. Upper Extremity SSEPs  from bilateral Median Nerve stimulation:   Left Median Nerve Stimulation (MS):  An evoked potential was recorded at Erb_s point at 9.7 ms and at the cervical spine at a peak latency of 12.3 ms.  An NP response complex was recorded at the right parietal cortex with peak latencies of 21.0 ms and 28.5 ms (N20/P30), respectively.   Interpretation:          The somatosensory evoked potentials from the left median nerve are within normal limits.    Right Median Nerve Stimulation (MD):  An evoked potential was recorded at Erb_s point at 9.0 ms and at the cervical spine at a peak latency of 13.3 ms.  An NP response complex was recorded at the left parietal cortex with peak latencies of 20.5 ms and 28.5 ms (N20/P30), respectively.  Interpretation:          The somatosensory evoked potentials from the right median nerve are within normal limits.      2. Lower Extremity SSEPs  from bilateral Posterior Tibial Nerve stimulation:   Left Posterior Tibial Nerve Stimulation (TS):  An evoked potential was recorded at the popliteal fossa at 7.8 ms. The evoked potential at the cervical spine was recorded at a peak latency of 24.7 ms.  A positive peak (P40) was recorded over midline parietal cortex at a peak latency of 38.8 ms.  Interpretation:          The somatosensory evoked potentials from the left posterior tibial nerve are within normal limits.  Right Posterior Tibial Nerve Stimulation (TD):  An evoked potential was recorded at the popliteal fossa at 7.0 ms and at the cervical spine at a peak latency of 20.5 ms.  A positive peak (P40) was recorded over midline parietal cortex at a peak latency of 39.3 ms.  Interpretation:          The somatosensory evoked potentials from the right posterior tibial nerve are within normal limits.    3. Brainstem Auditory Evoked Responses (BSER)  from bilateral auditory, click stimulation:   Left Auditory Stimulation (AS):  Waves II, III and a Wave IV/V response complex were recorded at peak latencies of 3.1, 4.7 and 6.5 ms, respectively.  Interpretation:          The brainstem responses from left auditory stimulation are within normal limits.   Right Auditory Stimulation (AD):  Waves II, III and a Wave IV/V response complex were recorded at peak latencies of 2.7, 4.7 and 6.2 ms, respectively.  Interpretation:          The brainstem responses from right auditory stimulation are within normal limits.     4. Impression:          SSEPs from MS, MD, TS and TD and BSERs from AS and AD are all within normal limits.

column169: 1. Upper Extremity SSEPs  from Right Median Nerve stimulation:   Technique:    Stimulation of the left (MS)  and right (MD) median nerves was performed with stimulating electrodes positioned at the wrist, 1 cm apart with the positive electrode proximal to the negative electrode.  A uniform stimulus rate of  2.35Hz was used.  Two hundred and fifty six responses were averaged for each epoch.  Two epochs were obtained for each stimulus condition, including controls (no stimulus applied).  The observation interval was 100 ms.    Results:      Left Median Nerve Stimulation (MS):  An evoked potential was recorded at Erb_s point at 10.3 ms and at the cervical spine at a peak latency of 14.5 ms.  An NP response complex was not recorded at the right parietal cortex.  Interpretation:          The somatosensory evoked potentials from the left median nerve are normal up to the level of the medulla and are absent at the level of the right parietal lobe, suggestive of a complete lesion and/or compression at the level of the upper brainstem, diencephalon  and/or parietal cortex, on the right side.   Right Median Nerve Stimulation (MD):  An evoked potential was recorded at Erb_s point at 10.8 ms and at the cervical spine at a peak latency of 14.7 ms.  An NP response complex was not recorded at the left parietal cortex.   Interpretation:          The somatosensory evoked potentials from the right median nerve are are normal up to the level of the medulla and are absent at the level of the left parietal lobe, suggestive of a complete lesion and/or compression at the level of the upper brainstem, diencephalon  and/or parietal cortex, on the left side.     2. Lower Extremity SSEPs  from bilateral Posterior Tibial Nerve stimulation:   Technique:    Stimulation of left (TS) and right (TD) tibial nerves was performed simultaneously, with stimulation electrodes positioned at the medial malleolous, with the positive electrode proximal.  A uniform stimulus rate of  2.35Hz was used. Two hundred and fifty six responses were averaged for each epoch.  Two epochs were obtained for each stimulus condition, including controls (no stimulus applied).  The observation interval was 100 ms.   Results:           Left Posterior Tibial Nerve Stimulation (TS):  An evoked potential was recorded at the popliteal fossa at 13.0 ms. The evoked potential at the cervical spine was recorded at a peak latency of 34.0 ms.  An NP response complex was not recorded at the right parietal cortex .  Interpretation:          The somatosensory evoked potentials from the left posterior tibial nerve are normal up to the level of the medulla and are absent at the level of the right parietal lobe, suggestive of a complete lesion and/or compression at the level of the upper brainstem, diencephalon  and/or mesial parietal cortex, on the right side.   Right Posterior Tibial Nerve Stimulation (TD):  An evoked potential was recorded at the popliteal fossa at 14.7 ms. The evoked potential at the cervical spine was recorded at a peak latency of 36.2 ms.  An NP response complex was not recorded at the left parietal cortex   Interpretation:          The somatosensory evoked potentials from the right posterior tibial nerve are normal up to the level of the medulla and are absent at the level of the left parietal lobe, suggestive of a complete lesion and/or compression at the level of the upper brainstem, diencephalon  and/or mesial parietal cortex, on the left side.     3. Brainstem Auditory Evoked Responses (BSER)  from bilateral auditory, click stimulation:   The right (AD) and left (AS) ears were stimulated independently, using alternating rarefractive and condensative clicks with at least an 95 dbSPL intensity level. A uniform stimulus rate of 17.5 Hz was used. White noise was applied to the contralateral ear at 70 dbSPL. The observation interval was 15 ms. One thousand and twenty four responses were averaged for each epoch.   Left Auditory Stimulation (AS):  Waves I,II,  III and a Wave IV/V response complex were recorded at peak latencies of 2.0, 3.5, 4.1 and 6.0 ms, respectively.  Interpretation:          The brainstem responses from left auditory stimulation are of good morphology and are within normal limits.  Right Auditory Stimulation (AD):  Waves I, II, III and a Wave IV/V response complex were recorded at peak latencies of 2.0, 3.6, 4.2 and 6.1 ms, respectively.  Interpretation:          The brainstem responses from right auditory stimulation are of good morphology and are within normal limits.      4. Impression:          Cortical SSEPs from MS, MD, TS, TD are absent and support a severe ischemic injury bilaterally of the parietal lobes.

Lower Extremity SSEPs  from bilateral Posterior Tibial Nerve stimulation:   Technique:    Stimulation of left (TS) and right (TD) tibial nerves was performed simultaneously, with stimulation electrodes positioned at the medial malleolous, with the positive electrode proximal.  A uniform stimulus rate of  2.35Hz was used. Two hundred and fifty six responses were averaged for each epoch.  Two epochs were obtained for each stimulus condition, including controls (no stimulus applied).  The observation interval was 100 ms.   Results:           Left Posterior Tibial Nerve Stimulation (TS):  An evoked potential was recorded at the popliteal fossa at 12.8 ms. The evoked potential at the cervical spine was recorded at a peak latency of 31.2 ms.  An NP response complex was recorded over midline parietal cortex at peak latencies of 43.0 ms and 49.3 ms, respectively  Interpretation:          The somatosensory evoked potentials from the left posterior tibial nerve are abnormally delayed, suggestive of a lesion or compression above the inferior brainstem on the right side. The evoked potential at the cervical spine was recorded at a peak latency of 32.3 ms. One thousand and twenty four responses were averaged for each epoch. Interpretation:          The somatosensory evoked potentials from the left posterior tibial nerve are within normal limits up to the level of the ipsilateral medulla, above which the absent right cortical SSEP is suggestive of a complete injury of the somatosensory pathways above the level of the medulla on the right side. Upper Extremity SSEPs  from bilateral Median Nerve stimulation:   Results:      Left Median Nerve Stimulation (MS):  An evoked potential was recorded at Erb_s point at 12.7 ms and at the cervical spine at a peak latency of 16.3 ms.  An NP response complex was not recorded at the right parietal cortex.   Interpretation:          The somatosensory evoked potentials from the left median nerve are normal at the level of the inferior brainstem on the left side and absent at the right parietal cortex, suggestive of a significant lesion at the level of the superior brainstem and/or cerebral cortex on the right side.   Right Median Nerve Stimulation (MD):  An evoked potential was recorded at Erb_s point at 12.0 ms and at the cervical spine at a peak latency of 16.3 ms.  An NP response complex was not recorded at the left parietal cortex.   Interpretation:          The somatosensory evoked potentials from the right median nerve are normal at  the level of the inferior brainstem on the right side and absent at the left parietal cortex, suggestive of a significant lesion at the level of the superior brainstem and/or cerebral cortex on the left side.     2. Lower Extremity SSEPs  from bilateral Posterior Tibial Nerve stimulation:   Results:           Left Posterior Tibial Nerve Stimulation (TS):  An evoked potential was recorded at the popliteal fossa at 14.3 ms. The evoked potential at the cervical spine was recorded at 38.3 ms.   The cortical SSEP was not recorded over midline parietal cortex.   Interpretation:          The somatosensory evoked potentials from the left posterior tibial nerve are abnormal at the level of the inferior brainstem on the left side and absent at the right parietal cortex, suggestive of significant lesions at the level of the left side brainstem and/or cerebral cortex on the right side.   Right Posterior Tibial Nerve Stimulation (TD):  An evoked potential was recorded at the popliteal fossa at 12.3 ms and at the cervical spine at 36.3 ms.   The cortical SSEP was not recorded over midline parietal cortex.  Interpretation:          The somatosensory evoked potentials from the right posterior tibial nerve are abnormal at the level of the inferior brainstem on the right side and absent at the left parietal cortex, suggestive of significant lesions at the level of the right side brainstem and/or cerebral cortex on the left side.     3. Brainstem Auditory Evoked Responses (BSER)  from bilateral auditory, click stimulation:   Left Auditory Stimulation (AS):  Waves I, II, III and a IV/V response complex were recorded at peak latencies of 1.9, 3.1, 4.5 and 7.7 ms, respectively.  Interpretation:          The brainstem responses from left auditory stimulation are barely discernible and of extremely poor morphology and are abnormally delayed at the level of the superior brainstem on the right side.    Right Auditory Stimulation (AD):  Waves I, II, III, IV and V were recorded at peak latencies of 1.9, 3.2, 4.9, 7.1 and 7.9 ms, respectively  Interpretation:       The brainstem responses from right auditory stimulation are of poor morphology and are abnormally delayed at the level of the superior brainstem on the left side.    4. Impression:          Cortical SSEPs are absent x4 limb SSEPs. Lower extremity subcortical brainstem SSEPs x2 are abnormal. The BSERs from AS and AD are abnormal at the level of the superior brainstem. These data support bilateral and diffuse injuries at the level of the superior brainstem bilaterally and further severe/complete injuries at the supratentorial  level of the thalamus and/or parietal lobes, bilaterally.

column169: 1. Upper Extremity SSEPs  from bilateral  Median Nerve stimulation:  Results:     Left Median Nerve Stimulation (MS): An evoked potential was recorded at Erb's point at 11.7 ms and at the cervical spine at a peak latency of 15.7 ms. A Negative N20 response was recorded at the right parietal cortex with a peak latency of 37.3 ms while the subsequent P30 cortical SSEP was recorded at 45.3 ms.  Interpretation:         The somatosensory evoked potentials from the left median nerve are within normal limits up to the level of the left inferior brainstem, above which the cortical SSEPs are very delayed, suggestive of a major injury or compression of the somatosensory pathway at the level of the superior brainstem and/or parietal lobe on the right side.    Right Median Nerve Stimulation (MD): An evoked potential was recorded at Erb's point at 11.0 ms and at the cervical spine at a peak latency of 14.7 ms. Very small amplitude and delayed cortical SSEPs were  recorded at the left  parietal cortex with peak latencies of 40.7 and 49.3 ms, respectively.  Interpretation:         The somatosensory evoked potentials from the right median nerve are within normal limits up to the level of the right inferior brainstem above which, the cortical SSEPs are  abnormally delayed, suggestive of a major lesion and/or compression at the level of the superior brainstem and/or parietal lobe on the left side.    2. Lower Extremity SSEPs  from bilateral Posterior Tibial Nerve stimulation:  Results:          Left Posterior Tibial Nerve Stimulation (TS): An evoked potential was recorded at the popliteal fossa at 8.3 ms. A subcortical SSEP was recorded at 32.0 ms.   An NP response complex was recorded over midline parietal cortex at peak latencies of 47.0 ms and 66.8 ms, respectively.  Interpretation:         The somatosensory evoked potentials from the left posterior tibial nerve are of poor morphology and are abnormally delayed, suggestive of a lesion or compressions above the level of the inferior brainstem on the right side and/or at the level of the right parietal cortex.    Right Posterior Tibial Nerve Stimulation (TD): An evoked potential was recorded at the popliteal fossa at 9.7 ms. A subcortical SSEP was recorded at 33.0 ms.   An NP response complex was recorded over midline parietal cortex at peak latencies of 40.3 ms and 48.0 ms, resepectively.   Interpretation:         The somatosensory evoked potentials from the right posterior tibial nerve are of poor morphology and are abnormally delayed, suggestive of a lesion or compressions above the inferior brainstem on the left side and/or at the level of the left parietal cortex.     3. Brainstem Auditory Evoked Responses (BSER)  from bilateral auditory, click stimulation:   Left Auditory Stimulation (AS): Waves I, III, IV and V were recorded at peak latencies of  2.1, 4.6, 5.8 and 6.7 ms, respectively. Interpretation:         The brainstem responses from left auditory stimulation are of good morphology and are abnormally delayed, suggestive of a lesion or compression at the level of the superior brainstem on the right side.  Right Auditory Stimulation (AD): Waves I, III, IV and V were recorded at peak latencies of 2.1, 4.4, 6.9 and 7.7 ms, respectively. Interpretation:         The brainstem responses from right auditory stimulation are of good  morphology and are abnormally delayed, suggestive of a lesion or compression at the level of the superior brainstem on the left side.   4. Impression:         Cortical SSEPs from MS, MD, PS and PD are all abnormal while subcortical SSEPs generated at the inferior brainstem from all four limbs are normal. AS and AD are abnormal at the level of the superior brainstem, bilaterally. This pattern is suggestive of diffuse injuries and/or lesions at the level of the superior brainstem, bilaterally and further diffuse injuries/lesions at the level of the parietal cortex, bilaterally.

column169: 1. Upper Extremity SSEPs  from bilateral  Median Nerve stimulation:  Results:     Left Median Nerve Stimulation (MS): An evoked potential was recorded at Erb's point at 10.0 ms and at the cervical spine at a peak latency of 14.0 ms. A Negative N20 response was recorded at the right parietal cortex with a peak latency of 45.7 ms while the subsequent P30 cortical SSEP was not recorded.  Interpretation:         The somatosensory evoked potentials from the left median nerve are within normal limits up to the level of the right parietal cortex at which the primary cortical SSEP (P30) was absent, suggestive of a right cortical level injury or lesion.    Right Median Nerve Stimulation (MD): An evoked potential was recorded at Erb's point at 9.3 ms and at the cervical spine at a peak latency of 13.7 ms. The negative N20 response was recorded at the left parietal cortex with a peak latency of 23.3 ms while the subsequent P30 cortical SSEP was recorded at 42.3 ms.  Interpretation:         The somatosensory evoked potentials from the right median nerve are within normal limits up to the level of the left parietal cortex at which the primary cortical SSEP (P30) was abnormally delayed, suggestive of a left cortical level injury or lesion.     2. Lower Extremity SSEPs  from bilateral Peroneal Nerve stimulation:  Results:          Left Peroneal Nerve Stimulation (PS): The subcortical SSEP was recorded at 37.7 ms.   An NP response complex was recorded over midline parietal cortex at peak latencies of 49.0 ms and 61.2 ms, respectively.  Interpretation:         The somatosensory evoked potentials from the left peroneal nerve are of poor morphology and are abnormally delayed, suggestive of a lesion or compressions at and above the level of the inferior brainstem on the left side and subsequently at the level of the right parietal cortex.    Right Peroneal Nerve Stimulation (PD): The subcortical SSEP was recorded at 33.3 ms. A primary cortical SSEP was recorded over midline parietal cortex at a peak latency of 48.7 ms while the P40 cortical SSEP was not recorded.  Interpretation:         The somatosensory evoked potentials from the right peroneal nerve are of poor morphology and are abnormally delayed, suggestive of a lesion or compressions at and above the right inferior brainstem and subsequently at the level of the left parietal cortex.     3. Brainstem Auditory Evoked Responses (BSER)  from bilateral auditory, click stimulation:   Left Auditory Stimulation (AS): Waves I, II, III, IV and V were recorded at peak latencies of  2.2, 3.2, 4.4, 5.7 and 6.6 ms, respectively. Interpretation:         The brainstem responses from left auditory stimulation are of good morphology and are abnormally delayed, suggestive of a lesion or compression at the level of the superior brainstem on the right side.  Right Auditory Stimulation (AD): Waves I, II, III, IV and V were recorded at peak latencies of 2.3, 3.4, 4.6, 5.6 and 6.6 ms, respectively. Interpretation:         The brainstem responses from right auditory stimulation are of good  morphology and are abnormally delayed, suggestive of a lesion or compression at the level of the superior brainstem on the left side.   4. Impression:         Cortical SSEPs from MS, MD, PS and PD are absent or abnormal. Subcortical SSEPs from PS and PD are abnormal at the level of the inferior brainstem and the BSERs from both AS and AD are abnormal at the level of the superior brainstem, bilaterally. This pattern is suggestive of diffuse injuries and/or lesions at the level of the inferior brainstem and superior brainstem, bilaterally and further diffuse injuries/lesions at the level of the parietal cortex, bilaterally.

column169: Addendum by CRAMMOND PhD, DONALD J on March 19, 2018 4:59 PM (Verified) 1. Upper Extremity SSEPs  from bilateral Median Nerve stimulation:  Results:     Left Median Nerve Stimulation (MS): An evoked potential was recorded at Erb's point at 9.7 ms and at the cervical spine at a peak latency of 13.3 ms. The Cortical SSEP response complex was not recorded at the right parietal cortex.  Interpretation:         The somatosensory evoked potentials from the left median nerve are normal up to the level of the inferior brainstem on the left side and are absent at the right parietal cortex, suggestive of a significant lesion at the level of the somatosensory cortex on the right side.  Right Median Nerve Stimulation (MD): An evoked potential was recorded at Erb's point at 9.7 ms and at the cervical spine at a peak latency of 13.0 ms. The Cortical SSEP response complex was not recorded at the left parietal cortex.  Interpretation:         The somatosensory evoked potentials from the right median nerve are normal up to the level of the inferior brainstem on the right side and are absent at the left parietal cortex, suggestive of a significant lesion at the level of the somatosensory cortex on the left side.   2. Lower Extremity SSEPs  from bilateral Posterior Tibial Nerve stimulation:  Results:          Left Posterior Tibial Nerve Stimulation (TS): An evoked potential was recorded at the popliteal fossa at 10.7 ms. The evoked potential at the cervical spine was recorded at 27.3 ms.  The cortical SSEP response complex was not recorded at the right parietal cortex.  Interpretation:         The somatosensory evoked potentials from the left posterior tibial nerve are normal up to the level of the inferior brainstem on the left side and are absent at the right parietal cortex, suggestive of a significant lesion at the level of the somatosensory cortex on the right side.  Right Posterior Tibial Nerve Stimulation (TD): An evoked potential was recorded at the popliteal fossa at 17.7 ms and at the cervical spine at 28.7 ms.  The cortical SSEP response complex was not recorded at the left parietal cortex. Interpretation:         The somatosensory evoked potentials from the right posterior tibial nerve are normal at the level of the inferior brainstem on the right side and are absent at the left parietal cortex, suggestive of a significant lesion at the level of the somatosensory cortex on the left side.   3. Brainstem Auditory Evoked Responses (BSER)  from bilateral auditory, click stimulation:  Left Auditory Stimulation (AS): Waves I, II, III, IV and V were recorded at peak latencies of 2.1, 3.3, 4.2, 5.6 and 6.6 ms, respectively.   Interpretation:         The brainstem responses from left auditory stimulation are within normal limits for age.  Right Auditory Stimulation (AD): Waves I, II, III, IV and V were recorded at peak latencies of 2.0, 3.3, 4.3, 5.7 and 7.1 ms, respectively.  Interpretation:      The brainstem responses from right auditory stimulation are of poor  morphology and are abnormally delayed, suggestive of a lesion or compression at the level of the superior brainstem on the left side.   4. Impression:         Subcortical brainstem SSEPs and the BSER from AS are normal x5 at the level of the bilateral inferior and right side superior brainstem. The BSER from AD is abnormal at the level of the superior brainstem on the left side. Cortical SSEPs are absent x4 limb SSEPs. These data support an incomplete injury at the level of the unilateral left superior brainstem with further bilateral and severe / complete injuries at the supratentorial level of the thalamus and/or parietal lobes, bilaterally.

column169: 1. Interpretation:         The somatosensory evoked potentials from the left median nerve are within normal limits up to the level of the left inferior brainstem, above which the cortical SSEPs are absent, suggestive of a significant lesion or compression of the somatosensory pathway at the level of the superior brainstem and/or parietal lobe on the right side.    Right Median Nerve Stimulation (MD): An evoked potential was recorded at Erb's point at 9.7 ms and at the cervical spine at a peak latency of 14.7 ms. The cortical SSEP was not recorded. Interpretation:         The somatosensory evoked potentials from the right median nerve are within normal limits up to the level of the right inferior brainstem above which, the cortical SSEPs are  absent, suggestive of a significant lesion or compression at the level of the superior brainstem and/or parietal lobe on the left side.    2. Lower Extremity SSEPs  from bilateral Posterior Tibial Nerve stimulation:  Results:          Left Posterior Tibial Nerve Stimulation (TS): An evoked potential was recorded at the popliteal fossa at 9.0 ms. The subcortical SSEP was not recorded.  The cortical SSEP was not recorded.  Interpretation:         The peripheral nerve evoked potential from the left posterior tibial nerve was recorded, above which the subcortical and cortical SSEPs are absent, suggestive of a significant lesion or compression at the level of the inferior brainstem on the left side and above the inferior brainstem on the right side.    Right Posterior Tibial Nerve Stimulation (TD): An evoked potential was recorded at the popliteal fossa at 8.7 ms. The subcortical SSEP was not recorded.  The cortical SSEP was not recorded.  Interpretation:         The peripheral nerve evoked potential from the right posterior tibial nerve was recorded, above which the subcortical and cortical SSEPs are absent, suggestive of a significant lesion or compressions at the level of the inferior brainstem on the right side and above the inferior brainstem on the left side.     3. Brainstem Auditory Evoked Responses (BSER)  from bilateral auditory, click stimulation:   Left Auditory Stimulation (AS): Waves I, II, III and IV were recorded at peak latencies of  2.4, 3.8, 5.0 and 6.1 ms, respectively. Wave V was not recorded. Interpretation:         The brainstem responses from left auditory stimulation are of poor morphology and are abnormally delayed and the absence of Wave V suggests a significant lesion or compression at the level of the superior brainstem on the right side.  Right Auditory Stimulation (AD): Waves I, II and III were recorded at peak latencies of 2.0, 3.5 and 4.7 ms, respectively. Waves IV and V were not recorded.  Interpretation:         The brainstem responses from right auditory stimulation are of poor  morphology and are abnormally delayed and the absence of Waves IV and V suggests a significant lesion or compression at the level of the superior brainstem on the left side.  4. Impression:         The abnormal and absent inferior and superior brainstem responses bilaterally, from TS, TD, AS and AD and the absence of all four cortical SSEPs from MS, MD, TS and TD, bilaterally, is suggestive of multiple diffuse injuries and/or lesions at the level of both the inferior and superior brainstem, bilaterally, and further diffuse injuries/lesions at the supratentorial levels of the parietal cortex, bilaterally.

column169: Upper extremity somatosensory evoked potentials:  Left median nerve stimulation resulted in a small amplitude peripheral (Erbs) response and absent subcortical and cortical (N20) responses. Right auditory stimulation resulted in a wave IV/V complex at a latency of 6.6ms.   Overall, this data indicates intact cortical function in the right hemisphere as evidenced by right median nerve SSEP data.  Although, there was no evidence of cortical function with left median nerve SSEP testing, the lack of a subcortical response and a weak ERb's point response raises the possibility of a primary peripheral nervous system lesion.  The lower extremity SSEP study was technically difficult secondary to edema and the lack of responses may be related to technical, rather than phsyiologic, issues.  There is intact brainstem function as evidenced by presence of BAEP waveforms.

column169: 1. Upper Extremity SSEPs  from bilateral  Median Nerve stimulation:  Left Median Nerve Stimulation (MS): The peripheral nerve evoked potential at Erb's point was recorded at 9.7 ms and the subcortical SSEP was recorded at a peak latency of 17.3 ms, which is abnormally delayed. The cortical SSEP (N20/P30) from the right parietal cortex was not recorded. Right Median Nerve Stimulation (MD): The peripheral nerve evoked potential at Erb's point was recorded at 9.7 ms and the subcortical SSEP was recorded at a peak latency of 17.3 ms, which is abnormally delayed. The cortical SSEP (N20/P30) from the left parietal cortex was not recorded.  2. Lower Extremity SSEPs  from bilateral Posterior Tibial Nerve stimulation:  Left Posterior Tibial Nerve Stimulation (TS): An evoked potential was recorded at the popliteal fossa at 10.3 ms and the subcortical SSEP was recorded at 35.7 ms, which is abnormally delayed.  The cortical SSEP (P40) from the right parietal cortex was was not recorded.  Right Posterior Tibial Nerve Stimulation (TD): An evoked potential was recorded at the popliteal fossa at 8.0 ms and the subcortical SSEP was recorded at 38.7 ms, which is abnormally delayed. The cortical SSEP (P40) from the left parietal cortex was not recorded.   3. Brainstem Auditory Evoked Responses (BSER)  from bilateral auditory, click stimulation:   Left Auditory Stimulation (AS): Waves I and II were recorded at peak latencies of  2.1 and 3.4 ms, respectively, which are within normal limits. Waves III, IV and V were recorded at peak latencies of  4.7, 6.3 and 7.0 ms, respectively, which are abnormally delayed.  Right Auditory Stimulation (AD): Waves I and II were recorded at peak latencies of  2.4 and 3.4 ms, respectively, which are within normal limits. Wave III, IV and V were recorded at peak latencies of  4.7, 6.0 and 7.0 ms, respectively, which are abnormally delayed.    4. Impression:         The abnormal subcortical SSEPs x4 and abnormal subcortical BSERs from AS and AD and the absence of cortical SSEPs from MS, MD, TS and TD, bilaterally, is suggestive of multiple diffuse major injuries and/or lesions at the levels of the inferior and superior brainstem, bilaterally and further diffuse and major injuries/lesions at the supratentorial level of the parietal cortex, bilaterally.
column185: Withdrawal for perceived poor neurological prognosis

column169: Bedside somatosensory evoked potentials in response to bilateral median and tibial nerve stimulation were recorded.  Left and right median nerve stimulation resulted in normal peripheral, brainstem and thalamocortical responses (N20/P30) bilaterally.  Left tibial nerve stimulation did not result in recordable peripheral, brainstem or cortical responses.  Right tiibal nerve stimulation resulted in small amplitude and delayed cortical responses. The patients legs, ankles and feet were extremely edematous and certainly contributed to the lack of recordable SSEPs. Additionally, brainstem potentials in response to bilateral auditory stimulation were recorded.  Independent left  ear stimulation resulted in present and normal brainstem responses. Right ear stimulation did not result in a recordable response.  Of note, the right ear canal appeared to be nearly occluded with wax so suffiicient stimulation was impossible to deliver.  Data do not indicate a bilateral supratentorial anoxic injury at this time.
column185: Withdrawal for perceived poor neurological prognosis

column169: Bedside somatosensory evoked potentials in response to bilateral median and tibial nerve stimulation were recorded.  Left and right median nerve stimulation resulted in peripheral and small brainstem responses but the thalamocortical responses (N20/P30) were absent bilaterally.  Left and right tibial nerve stimulation resulted in peripheral and small brainstem responses but the cortical responses were absent bilaterally.  Additionally, brainstem potentials in response to bilateral auditory stimulation were recorded.  Independent left and right ear stimulation resulted in only wave I and not other obligate brainstem waveforms were recorded bilaterally. Taken together data indicate a bilateral supratentorial anoxic injury that is accompanied by a poor prognosis although influence from her MS prexisting pathology can certainly affect waveforms.  That being said, I would still expect to see a delayed but present thalamocortical response.
